955	/// Returns a reference to the global lock associated with the `AtomicCell` at address `addr`.
956	///
957	/// This function is used to protect atomic data which doesn't fit into any of the primitive atomic
958	/// types in `std::sync::atomic`. Operations on such atomics must therefore use a global lock.
959	///
960	/// However, there is not only one global lock but an array of many locks, and one of them is
961	/// picked based on the given address. Having many locks reduces contention and improves
962	/// scalability.
963	#[inline]
964	#[must_use]
965	fn lock(addr: usize) -> &'static SeqLock {
966	    // The number of locks is a prime number because we want to make sure `addr % LEN` gets
967	    // dispersed across all locks.
968	    //
969	    // Note that addresses are always aligned to some power of 2, depending on type `T` in
970	    // `AtomicCell<T>`. If `LEN` was an even number, then `addr % LEN` would be an even number,
971	    // too, which means only half of the locks would get utilized!
972	    //
973	    // It is also possible for addresses to accidentally get aligned to a number that is not a
974	    // power of 2. Consider this example:
975	    //
976	    // ```
977	    // #[repr(C)]
978	    // struct Foo {
979	    //     a: AtomicCell<u8>,
980	    //     b: u8,
981	    //     c: u8,
982	    // }
983	    // ```
984	    //
985	    // Now, if we have a slice of type `&[Foo]`, it is possible that field `a` in all items gets
986	    // stored at addresses that are multiples of 3. It'd be too bad if `LEN` was divisible by 3.
987	    // In order to protect from such cases, we simply choose a large prime number for `LEN`.
988	    const LEN: usize = 67;
989	    const L: CachePadded<SeqLock> = CachePadded::new(SeqLock::new());
990	    static LOCKS: [CachePadded<SeqLock>; LEN] = [L; LEN];
991	
992	    // If the modulus is a constant number, the compiler will use crazy math to transform this into
993	    // a sequence of cheap arithmetic operations rather than using the slow modulo instruction.
994	    &LOCKS[addr % LEN]
995	}
